From:MCsweet
Stops,

Not to beat a dead horse, but I agree with Paul and continue to dislike the
idea of stop-loss orders for value investing. Is someone going to let a market
blip (sometimes intentionally triggered by unscrupulous market makers) override
their analysis? We are supposed to take advantage of Mr. Market, not let him
take advantage of us.

That being said, I will have to admit I just applied a "mental stop" to my
portfolio. I realized I got complacent, being basically fully invested and
enjoying the ride up even though I realized the oppportunities available
weren't that attractive and that I should get some more cash into the portfolio
as a protective measure.

I therefore sold a few of my more questionable securities today and will
probably look to pare off some more if the opportunity arises.

In this case, I am admitting I was over-invested going up into the mini-crash
we have had over the past week. Had I been properly positioned, I wouldn't be
feeling the need to sell anything in here. And the bonds/trust preferreds in my
IRA didn't help much either. They got whacked on a big widening of credit
spreads this week.

MC
